 Franco, two women writers with ties to the salon, appropriated and transformed tropes of female sexuality and male literary collaboration to position themselves within this homosocial literary economy. Based on archival work and Quaintance’s exceptional knowledge of Venetian dialect poetry, Textual Masculinity and the Exchange of Women in Renaissance Venice is an unprecedented window into the understudied world of Venetian literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aItalian poetryxHistory and criticismx16th century. 0aItalian poetryxMale authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aItalian poetryy16th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMasculinity in literature. 0aRenaissancexItalyxVenice. 0aRenaissancezItalyzVenice. 0aSalonsxHistoryx16th centuryxItalyxVenice. 0aSalonszItalyzVenicexHistoryy16th century. 0aSex in literature. 0aTriangles (Interpersonal relations) in literature. 0aWomen and literaturexHistoryx16th centuryxItalyxVenice. 0aWomen and literaturezItalyzVenicexHistoryy16th century. 0aWomen in literature. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144261952440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442619524423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442619524.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles